  "response_text": "A pale gray screen first displays a centered Burger King logo with very small legal text along the bottom. The scene then changes to a wooden tabletop seen from above. A dark blue Kelley Blue Book “Blue Book Used Car Guide” lies in the middle, with a blue pen to the right and a mug of dark coffee partly visible at the upper left. The book cover changes through different historical editions: a 1977 “Official Guide,” a 1960 guide, a 1948 guide, and then an older cream-and-blue “Motor Car Blue Book Values” booklet marked “October, 1926.” The surrounding tabletop stays consistent, with the coffee mug and pen shifting slightly in color and style as the guide editions change.\n\nA light-skinned hand enters at the bottom and opens the 1926 booklet. Inside, pages begin flipping rapidly. Each spread shows a side-view illustration or photo of a car with year labels and small pricing or specification tables beneath. The cars progress through decades: older black rounded cars, mid-century sedans and trucks, a red fastback, boxier late-century vehicles, then newer compact cars. The pages finally settle on a clean white spread labeled “Chevrolet Volt” on the left and “2017” on the right. A bright blue Chevrolet Volt is pictured across the open pages, with small data tables underneath. The hand points near the car’s front wheel, as if selecting it.\n\nThe printed blue car visually becomes a small three-dimensional blue car sitting on a simplified map surface. The map is white and pale gray with orange road lines, green blocks, and soft folded contours, set against a deep blue background. The car is shown in profile, parked on a blue circular marker. From above, the same hand lowers a small semicircular price gauge icon over the car. The gauge has green, white, and red segments with a Kelley Blue Book seal hanging below it. Tiny fine print appears along the bottom of the image.\n\nThe scene expands into a broader map. The blue car and its gauge shrink into one marker among many. Circular icons appear across the map, each containing a small car silhouette and a colored gauge, suggesting multiple vehicle-price data points in different places. A hand with pale pink fingernails moves over the map, spreading across the right side as if using a touchscreen. The map is now clearly displayed on a black tablet with rounded corners lying on the same wooden tabletop. Orange road lines, green areas, and blue water shapes fill the tablet screen, while several round vehicle-and-gauge markers are scattered across it.\n\nThe hand taps the central marker with the blue car. A white information panel opens over the map on the tablet. It shows a blue Chevrolet Volt on the left, the text “2017 Chevrolet Volt,” and a large colored gauge on the right. A green label above the gauge reads “Fair Market Range” followed by a dollar range, approximately “$19,304 – $23,950.” The gauge is divided into green, white, and red sections, with the Kelley Blue Book seal at the bottom. The fingertip rests near the seal, emphasizing the price indicator.\n\nThe tablet display slides to a plain white surface where a black car key fob with a blue rectangular tag lies near the center. The same hand reaches in, picks up the keys, and turns them in the palm. The blue tag and metal key ring swing as the hand closes around them, visually suggesting taking possession of the car. The tablet screen then becomes mostly blank white.\n\nAgainst a blue background, a tablet reappears at an angle showing a Kelley Blue Book interface. A large gauge graphic animates in the center of the tablet screen, with green, white, and red segments and the Kelley Blue Book seal. The interface header at the top reads “Kelley Blue Book.” As the tablet settles, the blue Chevrolet Volt listing appears again with the price gauge. Above the tablet, a yellow circular icon and white text appear: “Kelley Blue Book Price Advisor.”",
